# Technical Roadmap

Sequenced by dependency, not time.
Tracks marked [PARALLEL] can be built simultaneously once their dependencies are met.
Everything in a layer can start as soon as the layer above it is complete.

---

## Layer 0 — Foundation (blocks everything)

- [x] Define core data model: `Building`, `Route`, `Stop`, `Category`, `HistoricalRecord`
- [ ] Establish data pipeline: Kartverket + Planinnsyn (Norway) + UNESCO public API + Google Places
- [x] Native maps SDK integration scaffolding: Apple Maps (MapKit), Google Maps, fallback to OpenStreetMap
- [x] Project architecture: monorepo structure, API layer, mobile client (React Native or Swift/Kotlin native), offline storage strategy

---

## Layer 1 — Core (sequential)

- [x] Building and landmark database: ingest, normalize, and store records from connected data sources
- [x] Route generation engine: takes user location + filters → returns ordered list of stops with walking path
- [x] Filter system: by typology (new build, medieval, civic, transformation, under construction, UNESCO, landmark), era, and distance
- [x] Building detail view: name, description, architect, year, category, archive images, historical context
- [x] Map view: route overlay, stop markers, current position, next-stop navigation handoff to native maps app

---

## Layer 2 — [PARALLEL tracks]

**Track A — Offline Mode:**
- [ ] Route serialization: package all stops, map tiles, images, and audio into a downloadable bundle
- [ ] Local cache management: store, update, and delete offline routes
- [ ] Offline-aware UI: clear indicators when operating without connection

**Track B — Voice Tour Guide:**
- [ ] Geofencing engine: detect arrival within radius of each stop
- [ ] Audio narration system: TTS or pre-recorded audio activates automatically on arrival
- [ ] Guide content pipeline: structured scripts per building, authored or AI-generated and editorially reviewed
- [ ] Background audio support: guide plays while screen is locked or maps app is open

**Track C — Health & Fitness Integration:**
- [ ] Step count and distance calculation per route (pre-walk estimate)
- [ ] Apple HealthKit + Google Fit integration: log completed walks
- [ ] Fitness goal route mode: user selects target (5k / 10k / 15k / 20k steps) → app generates route that hits the goal
- [ ] Post-walk summary: steps walked, distance, buildings visited, calories (estimated)

**Track D — Discovery & Editorial:**
- [ ] Curated collections: "Brutalist Oslo", "Starchitects of Barcelona", "UNESCO World Heritage Walk"
- [ ] Search and browse: find routes by city, theme, duration, or step count
- [ ] Saved routes and favorites
- [ ] "What's nearby?" mode: shows culturally significant buildings within walking radius of current location

---

## Layer 3 — Enhanced Experiences

- [ ] Historical AR view: camera overlay showing building facades as they appeared in historical archive images (phone camera first, Meta glasses second)
- [ ] City archive deep integration: pull floor plans, construction drawings, planning documents where available (Planinnsyn, municipal archives)
- [ ] Pit stop suggestions: coffee shops and restaurants along the route, surfaced at appropriate moments (mid-route, post-walk)
- [ ] Accessibility route options: step-free alternatives, gradient indicators, bench locations
- [ ] Multi-day itinerary mode: plan a full trip across several days with culturally themed days

---

## Layer 4 — Platform & Partnerships

- [ ] App Store submission: Apple App Store + Google Play, targeting Travel and Lifestyle editorial placement
- [ ] Institutional API agreements: Visit Norway, Visit Oslo, national heritage registries, city tourism boards
- [ ] White-label / embed option: let Visit-pages and cultural institutions embed routes in their own apps or websites
- [ ] Analytics and feedback loop: route completion rates, most-visited stops, drop-off points, user ratings per building
- [ ] Referral and sharing: share a route as a link that opens in the app or renders as a web preview
